Explanation:
- I extracted every route defined with the admin_api.route decorator in app/api/cms/admin.py. Each decorator contains a literal string path in this file; those literal strings are reported as the path values, converting Flask-style parameters (<int:uid>, <int:gid>) to the requested curly-brace format ({uid}, {gid}). If the same path is bound to different handlers for different HTTP methods (e.g., DELETE and PUT on /user/{uid} and on /group/{gid}), each binding is listed separately with its handler function.
- For every entry:
  - implementation_present is true because the handler function body is defined in this same source file.
  - is_prefix is false because the decorators specify full route strings (no indication in this file that they are intentionally prefixes).
  - is_literal is true because the route path strings appear literally in the source code.
  - is_derived is false because none of these routes are created via naming conventions instead of explicit route strings in this file.
  - is_restful is true because these endpoints represent resource-oriented HTTP operations (user/group/permission management).
  - is_test is false because none of the handlers are test-only endpoints.
- Note: The blueprint name ("admin") may be registered with a URL prefix elsewhere in the project (not shown in this file). I did not attempt to resolve such an external prefix; I reported the literal paths as they appear in this file, as required.

path.description: The HTTP request path, which must begin with a forward slash (/) and have path parameters wrapped in curly braces ({}). Set this to null if it cannot be determined.
path.title: Path

handler.description: The function, class, class method, or object that handles the HTTP request. Use exactly "anonymous" to denote an anonymous implementation.
handler.title: Handler

handler_in_same_file.description: Whether the handler's implementation is present in the same source code file, rather than being imported.
handler_in_same_file.title: Handler In Same File

path_is_prefix.description: Whether the path string is a prefix rather than a full path.
path_is_prefix.title: Path Is Prefix

path_from_string_literal.description: Whether the path string is extracted from a literal string defined in the source code.
path_from_string_literal.title: Path From String Literal

path_from_naming_convention.description: Whether the path string is derived from a naming convention supported by the framework.
path_from_naming_convention.title: Path From Naming Convention

is_restful_api.description: Whether the API entry is for a RESTful API, rather than other types of APIs.
is_restful_api.title: Is Restful Api
